msgid "Reference"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:66
msgid ""
"Like other elements in Blender, Curve control points can be grabbed/moved "
"(:kbd:`G`), rotated (:kbd:`R`) or scaled (:kbd:`S`) as described in the "
":doc:`Basic Transformations </3d_interaction/transformations/basics>` "
"section. When in :guilabel:`Edit` mode, :doc:`proportional editing "
"</3d_interaction/transform_control/proportional_edit>` is also available for"
" transformation actions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:70
msgid "Snapping"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:79
msgid ""
":doc:`Mesh snapping </modeling/meshes/snapping>` also works with curve "
"components. Both control points and their handles will be affected by "
"snapping, except for within itself (other components of the active curve). "
"Snapping works with 2D curves but points will be constrained to the local XY"
" axes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:83
msgid "Deforming Tools"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:92
msgid ""
"The :guilabel:`To Sphere`, :guilabel:`Shear`, :guilabel:`Wrap` and "
":guilabel:`Push/Pull` transform tools are described in the "
":doc:`Transformations </3d_interaction/transformations>` sections. The two "
"other tools, :guilabel:`Tilt` and :guilabel:`Shrink/Fatten Radius` are "
"related to :doc:`Curve Extrusion </modeling/curves/editing/advanced>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:96
msgid "Smoothing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:105
msgid ""
"Curve smoothing is available through the specials menu. For Bézier curves, "
"this smoothing operation currently only smooths the positions of control "
"points and not their tangents. End points are also constrained when "
"smoothing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:111
msgid "Mirror"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:121
msgid ""
"The :guilabel:`Mirror` tool is also available, behaving exactly as with "
":doc:`mesh vertices </modeling/meshes/editing/deforming/mirror>`,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:128
msgid "Set Bézier Handle Type"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:139
msgid ""
"Handle types are a property of :doc:`Bézier curves. </modeling/curves>` and "
"can be used to alter features of the curve. For example, switching to "
":guilabel:`Vector handles` can be used to create curves with sharp corners. "
"Read the :doc:`Bézier curves </modeling/curves>` page for more details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:143
msgid "Extending Curves"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:153
msgid ""
"Once a curve is created you can add new segments (in fact, new control "
"points defining new segments), either by extruding, or placing new handles "
"with :kbd:`ctrl-lmb` clicks. Each new segment is added to one end of the "
"curve. A new segment will only be added if a single vertex, or handle, at "
"one end of the curve is selected. If two or more control points are "
"selected, a new Bézier closed curve is started."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:161
msgid ""
"Unlike mesh editing, you cannot create a new curve inside the edited object "
"by :kbd:`ctrl-lmb` -clicking without any control points selected. to do so, "
"you can cut an existing curve in two parts (by FIXME(TODO: Internal Link; "
"[[#Deleting Elements|deleting a segment]] )), FIXME(TODO: Internal Link; "
"[[#Duplication|copying]] ) an existing one (:kbd:`shift-D`), or add a new "
"one through the menu."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:171
msgid "Subdivision"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:182
msgid ""
"Curve subdivision simply subdivides all selected segments by adding one or "
"more control points between the selected segments. To control the number of "
"cuts, press :kbd:`W` to make a single subdivision. Then press :kbd:`F6` to "
"bring up the :guilabel:`Number of Cuts` menu."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:189
msgid "Duplication"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:199
msgid ""
"This command duplicates the selected control points, along with the curve "
"segments implicitly selected (if any). The copy is selected and placed in "
":guilabel:`Grab` mode, so you can move it to another place."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:205
msgid "Joining Curve Segments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:215
msgid ""
"Two open curves can be combined into one by creating a segment between the "
"two curves. To join two separated curves, select one end control point from "
"each curve then press :kbd:`F`. The two curves are joined by a segment to "
"become a single curve."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:225
msgid "Curves before and after joining"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:228
msgid ""
"Additionally, you can close a curve by joining the endpoints but note that "
"you can only join curves of the same type (i.e. Bézier with Bézier, NURBS "
"with NURBS)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:233
msgid "Separating Curves"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:243
msgid ""
"Curve objects that are made of multiple distinct curves can be separated "
"into their own objects by selecting the desired segments and pressing "
":kbd:`P`. Note, if there is only one curve in a Curve object, pressing "
":kbd:`P` will create a new Curve object with no control points."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:250
msgid "Deleting Elements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:260
msgid "The :guilabel:`Erase` pop-up menu of curves offers you three options:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:264
msgid "Selected"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:264
msgid ""
"This will delete the selected control points, *without* breaking the curve "
"(i.e. the adjacent points will be directly linked, joined, once the "
"intermediary ones are deleted). Remember that NURBS order cannot be higher "
"than its number of control points, so it might decrease when you delete some"
" control point. Of course, when only one point remains, there is no more "
"visible curve, and when all points are deleted, the curve itself is deleted."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:268
msgid "Segment"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:267
msgid ""
"This option is somewhat the opposite to the preceding one, as it will cut "
"the curve, without removing any control points, by erasing one selected "
"segment. This option always removes *only one segment* (the last "
"\"selected\" one), even when several are in the selection. So to delete all "
"segments in your selection, you'll have to repetitively use the same erase "
"option..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:272
msgid "All"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:271
msgid "As with meshes, this deletes everything in the object!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:279
msgid "Deleting Curve Selected"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:279
msgid "Deleting Curve segments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:284
msgid "Opening and Closing a Curve"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:294
msgid ""
"This toggles between an open curve and closed curve (Cyclic). Only curves "
"with at least one selected control point will be closed/open. The shape of "
"the closing segment is based on the start and end handles for Bézier curves,"
" and as usual on adjacent control points for NURBS. The only time a handle "
"is adjusted after closing is if the handle is an :guilabel:`Auto` one. "
"(*Open curve*) and (*Closed curve*) is the same Bézier curve open and "
"closed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:301
msgid ""
"This action only works on the original starting control-point or the last "
"control-point added. Deleting a segment(s) doesn't change how the action "
"applies; it still operates only on the starting and last control-points. "
"This means that :kbd:`Alt-C` may actually join two curves instead of closing"
" a single curve! Remember that when a 2D curve is closed, it creates a "
"renderable flat face."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:312
msgid "Open and Closed curves."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:316
msgid "Switch Direction"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:326
msgid ""
"This command will \"reverse\" the direction of any curve with at least one "
"selected element (i. e. the start point will become the end one, and *vice "
"versa*). This is mainly useful when using a curve as path, or using the "
"bevel and taper options."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:335
msgid "Converting Tools"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:338
msgid "Converting Curve Type"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:351
msgid "Set Spline Type button"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:354
msgid ""
"You can convert splines in a curve object between Bézier, NURBS, and Poly "
"curves. Press :kbd:`T` to bring up the Toolshelf. Clicking on the "
":guilabel:`Set Spline Type` button will allow you to select the Spline type "
"(Poly, Bézier or NURBS)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:359
msgid ""
"Note, this is not a \"smart\" conversion, i.e. Blender does not try to keep "
"the same shape, nor the same number of control points. For example, when "
"converting a NURBS to a Bézier, each group of three NURBS control points "
"become a unique Bézier one (center point and two handles)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:366
msgid "Convert Curve to Mesh"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:376
msgid ""
"There is also an \"external\" conversion, from curve to mesh, that only "
"works in :guilabel:`Object` mode. It transforms a :guilabel:`Curve` object "
"in a :guilabel:`Mesh` one, using the curve resolution to create edges and "
"vertices. Note that it also keeps the faces and volumes created by closed "
"and extruded curves."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:384
msgid "Convert Mesh to Curve"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:394
msgid ""
"Mesh objects that consist of a series of connected vertices can be converted"
" into curve objects. The resulting curve will be a Poly curve type, but can "
"be converted to have smooth segments as described above."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:400
msgid "Curve Parenting"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:409
msgid ""
"You can make other selected objects :doc:`children "
"</modeling/objects/groups_and_parenting#parenting_objects>` of one or three "
"control points :kbd:`ctrl-P`, as with mesh objects."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:411
msgid ""
"Select either 1 or 3 control points, then :kbd:`Ctrl-rmb` another object and"
" use :kbd:`Ctrl-P` to make a vertex parent."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:416
msgid "Hooks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:426
msgid ""
":doc:`Hooks </modifiers/deform/hooks>` can be added to control one or more "
"points with other objects."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:430
#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:442
msgid "Set Goal Weight"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/modeling/curves/editing.rst:440
msgid ""
"This sets the \"goal weight\" of selected control points, which is used when"
" a curve has Soft Body physics, forcing the curve to \"stick\" to their "
"original positions, based on the weight."
msgstr ""
